Under the optimal conditions, the as-constructed PEC sensor was employed to identify and detect ethyl acetate solutions of cholesterol with diverse concentrations. After being eluted with hexane for 15 min, FMIPs@CH3NH3PbI3@CNDs/ITO was soaked in the identification solution for 9 min, and then placed in 0.1 mol/L Na2SO4 solution for photocurrent detection. As shown in Fig. 7
                        A, the photocurrent response of the sensor weakened with the increase of cholesterol concentration. It had a linear relationship between the current change (ΔI) and the logarithm of cholesterol concentration (log C) in the range of 1.0 × 10−13–1.0 × 10−9 mol/L. The linear equation of the PEC sensor was ΔI (μA) = 3.1443 + 0.2253 log C (R2 = 0.9949) (Fig. 7B, curve a), and the limit of detection (LOD) was estimated to be 8.91 × 10−14 mol/L based on the standard deviation of the response and the slope (LOD = 3Sa/b). Compared to the previously reported studies, the developed PEC sensor demonstrated a wider linear range and lower detection limits (Table 1
                        ), indicating its excellent detection performance. Moreover, the imprinting efficiency can be evaluated by the imprinting factor which is commonly calculated from the ratio of slopes of the calibration plot constructed for the MIP and NIP sensors [68]. The calibration curve (curve b) for NIPs@CH3NH3PbI3@CNDs/ITO was also shown in Fig. 7B, and the linear equation was ΔI (μA) = 0.6438 + 0.0455 log C (R2 = 0.9896). Therefore, the imprinting factor of FMIPs@CH3NH3PbI3@CNDs/ITO sensor was calculated to be 4.95. The high imprinting factor indicated that FMIPs@CH3NH3PbI3@CNDs/ITO exhibited very high sensitivity to target cholesterol.
